# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pathfinding-navmesh
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] One major practical drawback is its $O(b^{d})$ space complexity where d is the depth of the shallowest solution (the length of the shortest path from the source node to any given goal node) and b is the branching factor (the maximum number of successors for any given state).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] In practical travel-routing systems, it is generally outperformed by algorithms that can pre-process the graph to attain better performance, as well as by memory-bounded approaches; however, A* is still the best solution in many cases.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Peter Hart, Nils Nilsson and Bertram Raphael of Stanford Research Institute (now SRI International) first published the algorithm in 1968.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] It can be seen as an extension of Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A* achieves better performance by using heuristics to guide its search.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The A* algorithm terminates once it finds the shortest path to a specified goal, rather than generating the entire shortest-path tree from a specified source to all possible goals.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A* was created as part of the Shakey project, which had the aim of building a mobile robot that could plan its own actions.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Nils Nilsson originally proposed using the Graph Traverser algorithm for Shakey's path planning.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Graph Traverser is guided by a heuristic function *h*(*n*), the estimated distance from node n to the goal node: it entirely ignores *g*(*n*), the distance from the start node to n.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Bertram Raphael suggested using the sum, *g*(*n*) + *h*(*n*).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Peter Hart invented the concepts we now call admissibility and consistency of heuristic functions.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A* was originally designed for finding least-cost paths when the cost of a path is the sum of its costs, but it has been shown that A* can be used to find optimal paths for any problem satisfying the conditions of a cost algebra.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The original 1968 A* paper contained a theorem stating that no A*-like algorithm could expand fewer nodes than A* if the heuristic function is consistent and A*'s tie-breaking rule is suitably chosen.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A* is an informed search algorithm, or a best-first search, meaning that it is formulated in terms of weighted graphs: starting from a specific starting node of a graph, it aims to find a path to the given goal node having the smallest cost (least distance travelled, shortest time, etc.).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] It does this by maintaining a tree of paths originating at the start node and extending those paths one edge at a time until the goal node is reached.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] At each iteration of its main loop, A* needs to determine which of its paths to extend.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] It does so based on the cost of the path and an estimate of the cost required to extend the path all the way to the goal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] where n is the next node on the path, *g*(*n*) is the cost of the path from the start node to n, and *h*(*n*) is a heuristic function that estimates the cost of the cheapest path from n to the goal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The heuristic function is problem-specific.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Typical implementations of A* use a priority queue to perform the repeated selection of minimum (estimated) cost nodes to expand.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] This priority queue is known as the *open set*, *fringe* or *frontier*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] At each step of the algorithm, the node with the lowest *f*(*x*) value is removed from the queue, the f and g values of its neighbors are updated accordingly, and these neighbors are added to the queue.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm continues until a removed node (thus the node with the lowest f value out of all fringe nodes) is a goal node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The f value of that goal is then also the cost of the shortest path, since h at the goal is zero in an admissible heuristic.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm described so far only gives the length of the shortest path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] To find the actual sequence of steps, the algorithm can be easily revised so that each node on the path keeps track of its predecessor.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] After this algorithm is run, the ending node will point to its predecessor, and so on, until some node's predecessor is the start node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] As an example, when searching for the shortest route on a map, *h*(*x*) might represent the straight-line distance to the goal, since that is physically the smallest possible distance between any two points.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] For a grid map from a video game, using the Taxicab distance or the Chebyshev distance becomes better depending on the set of movements available (4-way or 8-way).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic h satisfies the additional condition *h*(*x*) ≤ *d*(*x*, *y*) + *h*(*y*) for every edge (*x*, *y*) of the graph (where d denotes the length of that edge), then h is called monotone, or consistent.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] With a consistent heuristic, A* is guaranteed to find an optimal path without processing any node more than once and A* is equivalent to running Dijkstra's algorithm with the reduced cost *d'*(*x*, *y*) = *d*(*x*, *y*) + *h*(*y*) − *h*(*x*).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The A* algorithm has real-world applications.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] In this example, edges are railroads and h(x) is the great-circle distance (the shortest possible distance on a sphere) to the target.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The algorithm is searching for a path between Washington, D.C., and Los Angeles.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] There are a number of simple optimizations or implementation details that can significantly affect the performance of an A* implementation.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The first detail to note is that the way the priority queue handles ties can have a significant effect on performance in some situations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] If ties are broken so the queue behaves in a LIFO manner, A* will behave like depth-first search among equal cost paths (avoiding exploring more than one equally optimal solution).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] When a path is required at the end of the search, it is common to keep with each node a reference to that node's parent.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] At the end of the search, these references can be used to recover the optimal path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] If these references are being kept then it can be important that the same node doesn't appear in the priority queue more than once (each entry corresponding to a different path to the node, and each with a different cost).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A standard approach here is to check if a node about to be added already appears in the priority queue.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] If it does, then the priority and parent pointers are changed to correspond to the lower-cost path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A standard binary heap based priority queue does not directly support the operation of searching for one of its elements, but it can be augmented with a hash table that maps elements to their position in the heap, allowing this decrease-priority operation to be performed in logarithmic time.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Alternatively, a Fibonacci heap can perform the same decrease-priority operations in constant amortized time.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm, as another example of a uniform-cost search algorithm, can be viewed as a special case of A* where ⁠ $h(x)=0$ ⁠ for all *x*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] General depth-first search can be implemented using A* by considering that there is a global counter *C* initialized with a very large value.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Every time we process a node we assign *C* to all of its newly discovered neighbors.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] After every single assignment, we decrease the counter *C* by one.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Thus the earlier a node is discovered, the higher its ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠ value.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Both Dijkstra's algorithm and depth-first search can be implemented more efficiently without including an ⁠ $h(x)$ ⁠ value at each node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] On finite graphs with non-negative edge weights A* is guaranteed to terminate and is *complete*, i.e. it will always find a solution (a path from start to goal) if one exists.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] On infinite graphs with a finite branching factor and edge costs that are bounded away from zero ( ${\textstyle d(x,y)>\varepsilon >0}$ for some fixed $\varepsilon$ ), A* is guaranteed to terminate only if there exists a solution.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A search algorithm is said to be *admissible* if it is guaranteed to return an optimal solution.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic function used by A* is admissible, then A* is admissible.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Call a node *closed* if it has been visited and is not in the open set.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] We *close* a node when we remove it from the open set.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A basic property of the A* algorithm, which we'll sketch a proof of below, is that when ⁠ n ⁠ is closed, ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠ is an optimistic estimate (lower bound) of the true distance from the start to the goal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] So when the goal node, ⁠ g ⁠, is closed, ⁠ $f(g)$ ⁠ is no more than the true distance.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] On the other hand, it is no less than the true distance, since it is the length of a path to the goal plus a heuristic term.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Now we'll see that whenever a node ⁠ n ⁠ is closed, ⁠ $f(n)$ ⁠ is an optimistic estimate.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Let ⁠ P ⁠ be an optimal path from the start to the goal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Let ⁠ p ⁠ be the last closed node on ⁠ P ⁠ for which ⁠ $g(p)$ ⁠ is the true distance from the start to ⁠ p ⁠ (the start is one such vertex).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The next node in ⁠ P ⁠ has the correct ⁠ g ⁠ value, since it was updated when ⁠ p ⁠ was closed, and it is open since it is not closed.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The definitive study of the optimal efficiency of A* is due to Rina Dechter and Judea Pearl.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] They considered a variety of definitions of **Alts** and **P** in combination with A*'s heuristic being merely admissible or being both consistent and admissible.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The most interesting positive result they proved is that A*, with a consistent heuristic, is optimally efficient with respect to all admissible A*-like search algorithms on all "non-pathological" search problems.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Roughly speaking, their notion of the non-pathological problem is what we now mean by "up to tie-breaking".
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] This result does not hold if A*'s heuristic is admissible but not consistent.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] In that case, Dechter and Pearl showed there exist admissible A*-like algorithms that can expand arbitrarily fewer nodes than A* on some non-pathological problems.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Optimal efficiency is about the *set* of nodes expanded, not the *number* of node expansions (the number of iterations of A*'s main loop).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] When the heuristic being used is admissible but not consistent, it is possible for a node to be expanded by A* many times, an exponential number of times in the worst case.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] In such circumstances, Dijkstra's algorithm could outperform A* by a large margin.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] While the admissibility criterion guarantees an optimal solution path, it also means that A* must examine all equally meritorious paths to find the optimal path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] To compute approximate shortest paths, it is possible to speed up the search at the expense of optimality by relaxing the admissibility criterion.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Oftentimes we want to bound this relaxation, so that we can guarantee that the solution path is no worse than (1 + *ε*) times the optimal solution path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] This new guarantee is referred to as *ε*-admissible.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] As a heuristic search algorithm, the performance of A* is heavily influenced by the quality of the heuristic function ${\textstyle h(n)}$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] If the heuristic closely approximates the true cost to the goal, A* can significantly reduce the number of node expansions.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] On the other hand, a poor heuristic can lead to many unnecessary expansions.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] In the worst case, A* expands all nodes ${\textstyle n}$ for which ${\textstyle f(n)=g(n)+h(n)\leq C^{*}}$ , where ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ is the cost of the optimal goal node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Suppose there is a node ${\textstyle N'}$ in the open list with ${\textstyle f(N')>C^{*}}$ , and it's the next node to be expanded.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Since the goal node has ${\textstyle f(goal)=g(goal)+h(goal)=g(goal)=C^{*}}$ , and ${\textstyle f(N')>C^{*}}$ , the goal node will have a lower f-value and will be expanded before ${\textstyle N'}$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Therefore, A* never expands nodes with ${\textstyle f(n)>C^{*}}$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Assume there exists an optimal algorithm that expands fewer nodes than ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ in the worst case using the same heuristic.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] That means there must be some node ${\textstyle N'}$ such that ${\textstyle f(N')<C^{*}}$ , yet the algorithm chooses not to expand it.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Now consider a modified graph where a new edge of cost ${\textstyle \varepsilon }$ (with ${\textstyle \varepsilon >0}$ ) is added from ${\textstyle N'}$ to the goal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] If ${\textstyle f(N')+\varepsilon <C^{*}}$ , then the new optimal path goes through ${\textstyle N'}$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] However, since the algorithm still avoids expanding ${\textstyle N'}$ , it will miss the new optimal path, violating its optimality.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Therefore, no optimal algorithm including A* could expand fewer nodes than ${\textstyle C^{*}}$ in the worst case.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The worst-case complexity of A* is often described as ${\textstyle O(b^{d})}$ , where b is the branching factor and ${\textstyle d}$ is the depth of the shallowest goal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] While this gives a rough intuition, it does not precisely capture the actual behavior of A*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A more accurate bound considers the number of nodes with ${\textstyle f(n)\leq C^{*}}$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] This represents both the time and space complexity in the worst case.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] The space complexity of A* is roughly the same as that of all other graph search algorithms, as it keeps all generated nodes in memory.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] In practice, this turns out to be the biggest drawback of the A* search, leading to the development of memory-bounded heuristic searches, such as Iterative deepening A*, memory-bounded A*, and SMA*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A* is often used for the common pathfinding problem in applications such as video games, but was originally designed as a general graph traversal algorithm.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] It finds applications in diverse problems, including the problem of parsing using stochastic grammars in NLP.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Other cases include an Informational search with online learning.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] What sets A* apart from a greedy best-first search algorithm is that it takes the cost/distance already traveled, *g*(*n*), into account.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] Some common variants of Dijkstra's algorithm can be viewed as a special case of A* where the heuristic $h(n)=0$ for all nodes; in turn, both Dijkstra and A* are special cases of dynamic programming.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A* itself is a special case of a generalization of branch and bound.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A* is similar to beam search except that beam search maintains a limit on the numbers of paths that it has to explore.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/a-search-algorithm] A* can also be adapted to a bidirectional search algorithm, but special care needs to be taken for the stopping criterion.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Artificial intelligence (AI) in video games refers to the computational systems that control non-player characters (NPCs), generate dynamic game behavior, or simulate strategic decision-making.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In practice, the term covers a broad range of techniques drawn from computer science, control theory, and robotics rather than "true" artificial intelligence.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Moreover, academic AI—aimed at developing autonomous reasoning or learning—is distinct from game AI, whose goal is to deliver engaging, believable, and efficient behavior for players.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The term *CPU* in video games refer to the AI that control a NPC that could be a playable character in some other situations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In general, game AI does not, as might be thought and sometimes is depicted to be the case, mean a realization of an artificial person corresponding to an NPC in the manner of the Turing test or an artificial general intelligence.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some commentators in the video game industry have claimed that advances in game AI have transformed how players interact with digital systems more broadly.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Marketing discussions sometimes attribute human-like traits to game AI—such as personality or creative autonomy—but these are often scripted behaviors designed to mimic complexity rather than emergent cognition.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game playing was an area of research in AI from its inception.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the first examples of AI is the computerized game of Nim made in 1941 and published in 1942.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite being advanced technology in the year it was made, 20 years before *Pong*, the game took the form of a relatively small box and was able to regularly win games even against highly skilled players of the game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 1951, using the Ferranti Mark 1 machine of the University of Manchester, Christopher Strachey wrote a checkers program and Dietrich Prinz wrote one for chess.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These were among the first computer programs ever written.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Arthur Samuel's checkers program, developed in the middle 1950s and early 1960s, eventually achieved sufficient skill to challenge a respectable amateur.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Work on checkers and chess would culminate in the defeat of Garry Kasparov by IBM's Deep Blue computer in 1997.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first video games developed in the 1960s and early 1970s, like *Spacewar!*, *Pong*, and *Gotcha* (1973), were games implemented on discrete logic and strictly based on the competition of two players, without AI.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games that featured a single player mode with enemies started appearing in the 1970s.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first notable ones for the arcade appeared in 1974: the Taito game *Speed Race* (racing video game) and the Atari games *Qwak* (duck hunting light gun shooter) and *Pursuit* (fighter aircraft dogfighting simulator).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Two text-based computer games, *Star Trek* (1971) and *Hunt the Wumpus* (1973), also had enemies.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemy movement was based on stored patterns.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The incorporation of microprocessors would allow more computation and random elements overlaid into movement patterns.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Galaxian* (1979) added more complex and varied enemy movements, including maneuvers by individual enemies who break out of formation.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Pac-Man* (1980) introduced AI patterns to maze games, with the added quirk of different personalities for each enemy.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Karate Champ* (1984) later introduced AI patterns to fighting games.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *First Queen* (1988) was a tactical action RPG which featured characters that can be controlled by the computer's AI in following the leader.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The role-playing video game *Dragon Quest IV* (1990) introduced a "Tactics" system, where the user can adjust the AI routines of non-player characters during battle, a concept later introduced to the action role-playing game genre by *Secret of Mana* (1993).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games like *Madden Football*, *Earl Weaver Baseball* and *Tony La Russa Baseball* all based their AI in an attempt to duplicate on the computer the coaching or managerial style of the selected celebrity.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Madden, Weaver and La Russa all did extensive work with these game development teams to maximize the accuracy of the games.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later sports titles allowed users to "tune" variables in the AI to produce a player-defined managerial or coaching strategy.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The emergence of new game genres in the 1990s prompted the use of formal AI tools like finite-state machines.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Real-time strategy games taxed the AI with many objects, incomplete information, pathfinding problems, real-time decisions and economic planning, among other things.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The first games of the genre had notorious problems.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Herzog Zwei* (1989), for example, had almost broken pathfinding and very basic three-state state machines for unit control, and *Dune II* (1992) attacked the players' base in a beeline and used numerous cheats.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games in the genre exhibited more sophisticated AI.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Later games have used bottom-up AI methods, such as the emergent behaviour and evaluation of player actions in games like *Creatures* or *Black & White*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Façade* was released in 2005 and used interactive multiple way dialogs and AI as the main aspect of game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Games have provided an environment for developing artificial intelligence with potential applications beyond gameplay.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Examples include Watson, a Jeopardy!-playing computer; and the RoboCup tournament, where robots are trained to compete in soccer.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many experts complain that the "AI" in the term *game AI* overstates its worth, as game AI is not about intelligence, and shares few of the objectives of the academic field of AI.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Whereas "real AI" addresses fields of machine learning, decision making based on arbitrary data input, and even the ultimate goal of strong AI that can reason, "game AI" often consists of a half-dozen rules of thumb, or heuristics, that are just enough to give a good gameplay experience.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Historically, academic game-AI projects have been relatively separate from commercial products because the academic approaches tended to be simple and non-scalable.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial game AI has developed its own set of tools, which have been sufficient to give good performance in many cases.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game developers' increasing awareness of academic AI and a growing interest in computer games by the academic community is causing the definition of what counts as AI in a game to become less idiosyncratic.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Nevertheless, significant differences between different application domains of AI mean that game AI can still be viewed as a distinct subfield of AI.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In particular, the ability to legitimately solve some AI problems in games by cheating creates an important distinction.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, inferring the position of an unseen object from past observations can be a difficult problem when AI is applied to robotics, but in a computer game a NPC can simply look up the position in the game's scene graph.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Such cheating can lead to unrealistic behavior and so is not always desirable.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] But its possibility serves to distinguish game AI and leads to new problems to solve, such as when and how to cheat.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The major limitation to strong AI is the inherent depth of thinking and the extreme complexity of the decision-making process.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This means that although it would be then theoretically possible to make "smart" AI the problem would take considerable processing power.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI/heuristic algorithms are used in a wide variety of quite disparate fields inside a game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The most obvious is in the control of any NPCs in the game, although "scripting" (decision tree) is currently the most common means of control.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These handwritten decision trees often result in "artificial stupidity" such as repetitive behavior, loss of immersion, or abnormal behavior in situations the developers did not plan for.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding, another common use for AI, is widely seen in real-time strategy games.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding is the method for determining how to get a NPC from one point on a map to another, taking into consideration the terrain, obstacles and possibly "fog of war".
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Commercial videogames often use fast and simple "grid-based pathfinding", wherein the terrain is mapped onto a rigid grid of uniform squares and a pathfinding algorithm such as A* or IDA* is applied to the grid.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Instead of just a rigid grid, some games use irregular polygons and assemble a navigation mesh out of the areas of the map that NPCs can walk to.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As a third method, it is sometimes convenient for developers to manually select "waypoints" that NPCs should use to navigate; the cost is that such waypoints can create unnatural-looking movement.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, waypoints tend to perform worse than navigation meshes in complex environments.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Beyond static pathfinding, navigation is a sub-field of Game AI focusing on giving NPCs the capability to navigate in a dynamic environment, finding a path to a target while avoiding collisions with other entities (other NPC, players...) or collaborating with them (group navigation).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Navigation in dynamic strategy games with large numbers of units, such as Age of Empires (1997) or Civilization V (2010), often performs poorly; units often get in the way of other units.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than improve the Game AI to properly solve a difficult problem in the virtual environment, it is often more cost-effective to just modify the scenario to be more tractable.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If pathfinding gets bogged down over a specific obstacle, a developer may just end up moving or deleting the obstacle.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Many contemporary video games fall under the category of action, first-person shooter, or adventure.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In most of these types of games, there is some level of combat that takes place.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI's ability to be efficient in combat is important in these genres.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A common goal today is to make the AI more human or at least appear so.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One of the more positive and efficient features found in modern-day video game AI is the ability to hunt.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI originally reacted in a very black and white manner.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the player were in a specific area then the AI would react in either a complete offensive manner or be entirely defensive.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In recent years, the idea of "hunting" has been introduced; in this 'hunting' state the AI will look for realistic markers, such as sounds made by the character or footprints they may have left behind.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These developments ultimately allow for a more complex form of play.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With this feature, the player can actually consider how to approach or avoid an enemy.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is a feature that is particularly prevalent in the stealth genre.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another development in recent game AI has been the development of "survival instinct".
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In-game computers can recognize different objects in an environment and determine whether it is beneficial or detrimental to its survival.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Like a user, the AI can look for cover in a firefight before taking actions that would leave it otherwise vulnerable, such as reloading a weapon or throwing a grenade.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] There can be set markers that tell it when to react in a certain way.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the AI is given a command to check its health throughout a game then further commands can be set so that it reacts a specific way at a certain percentage of health.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] If the health is below a certain threshold then the AI can be set to run away from the player and avoid it until another function is triggered.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another example could be if the AI notices it is out of bullets, it will find a cover object and hide behind it until it has reloaded.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Actions like these make the AI seem more human.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there is still a need for improvement in this area.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another side-effect of combat AI occurs when two AI-controlled characters encounter each other; first popularized in the id Software game *Doom*, so-called 'monster infighting' can break out in certain situations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Specifically, AI agents that are programmed to respond to hostile attacks will sometimes attack *each other* if their cohort's attacks land too close to them.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the case of *Doom*, published gameplay manuals even suggest taking advantage of monster infighting in order to survive certain levels and difficulty settings.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural content generation (PCG) is an AI technique to autonomously create ingame content through algorithms with minimal input from designers.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG is typically used to dynamically generate game features such as levels, NPC dialogue, and sounds.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers input specific parameters to guide the algorithms into making content for them.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG offers numerous advantages from both a developmental and player experience standpoint.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game studios are able to spend less money on artists and save time on production.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are given a fresh, highly replayable experience as the game generates new content each time they play.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] PCG allows game content to adapt in real time to the player's actions.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative algorithms (a rudimentary form of AI) have been used for level creation for decades.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The iconic 1980 dungeon crawler computer game *Rogue* is a foundational example.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players are tasked with descending through the increasingly difficult levels of a dungeon to retrieve the Amulet of Yendor.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The dungeon levels are algorithmically generated at the start of each game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The save file is deleted every time the player dies.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithmic dungeon generation creates unique gameplay that would not otherwise be there as the goal of retrieving the amulet is the same each time.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The roguelike video game genre, derived from *Rogue*, feature games that use some type of procedural generation to provide near infinite replayability.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Opinions on total level generation as seen in games like *Rogue* can vary.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some developers can be skeptical of the quality of generated content and desire to create a world with a more "human" feel so they will use PCG more sparingly.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Consequently, they will only use PCG to generate specific components of an otherwise handcrafted level.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] A notable example of this is Ubisoft's 2017 tactical shooter *Tom Clancy's Ghost Recon Wildlands*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers used a pathfinding algorithm trained with a data set of real maps to create road networks that would weave through handcrafted villages within the game world.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is an intelligent use of PCG as the AI would have a large amount of real world data to work with and roads are straightforward to create.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, the AI would likely miss nuances and subtleties if it was tasked with creating a village where people live.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] As AI has become more advanced, developer goals are shifting to create massive repositories of levels from data sets.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2023, researchers from New York University and the University of the Witwatersrand trained a large language model to generate levels in the style of the 1981 puzzle game *Sokoban*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They found that the model excelled at generating levels with specifically requested characteristics such as difficulty level or layout.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, current models such as the one used in the study require large datasets of levels to be effective.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They concluded that, while promising, the high data cost of large language models currently outweighs the benefits for this application.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Continued advancements in the field will likely lead to more mainstream use in the future.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The musical score of a video game is an important expression of the emotional tone of a scene to the player.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sound effects such as the noise of a weapon hitting an enemy help indicate the effect of the player's actions.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generating these in real time creates an engaging experience for the player because the game is more responsive to their input.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] An example is the 2013 adventure game *Proteus* where an algorithm dynamically adapts the music based on the angle the player is viewing the ingame landscape from.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent breakthroughs in AI have resulted in the creation of advanced tools that are capable of creating music and sound based on evolving factors with minimal developer input.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such example is the MetaComposure music generator.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] MetaComposure is an evolutionary algorithm designed to generate original music compositions during real time gameplay to match the current mood of the environment.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The algorithm is able to assess the current mood of the game state through "mood tagging".
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Research indicates that there is a significant positive statistical correlation regarding player rated game engagement and the dynamically generated musical compositions when they accurately match their current emotions.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative tools similar to those used in LLMs and diffusion models like Midjourney and DALL-E have been used to generate in-game environments, and companies like Ubisoft have stated that they are experimenting with using AI to generate basic dialogue.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers at Roblox are using AI to generate 3D objects for players dubbed Cube 3D, an open-source AI that generates 3D objects based on the methods of LLMs to generate words.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Game AI often amounts to pathfinding and finite-state machines.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Pathfinding gets the AI from point A to point B, usually in the most direct way possible.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] State machines permit transitioning between different behaviors.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Monte Carlo tree search method provides a more engaging game experience by creating additional obstacles for the player to overcome.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The MCTS consists of a tree diagram in which the AI essentially plays tic-tac-toe.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Depending on the outcome, it selects a pathway yielding the next obstacle for the player.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In complex video games, these trees may have more branches, provided that the player can come up with several strategies to surpass the obstacle.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academic AI may play a role within game AI, outside the traditional concern of controlling NPC behavior.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Procedural-content generation: Creating elements of the game environment like environmental conditions, levels, and even music in an automated way.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] AI methods can generate new content or interactive stories.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Data mining on user behavior: This allows game designers to explore how people use the game, what parts they play most, and what causes them to stop playing, allowing developers to tune gameplay or improve monetization.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Alternate approaches to NPCs: These include changing the game set-up to enhance NPC believability and exploring social rather than individual NPC behavior.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Rather than procedural generation, some researchers have used generative adversarial networks (GANs) to create new content.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2018 researchers at Cornwall University trained a GAN on a thousand human-created levels for *Doom*; following training, the neural net prototype was able to design new playable levels on its own.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Similarly, researchers at the University of California prototyped a GAN to generate levels for Super Mario.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In 2020 Nvidia displayed a GAN-created clone of *Pac-Man*; the GAN learned how to recreate the game by watching 50,000 (mostly bot-generated) playthroughs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Non-player characters are entities within video games that are not controlled by players, but instead are managed by AI systems.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs contribute to the immersion, storytelling, and the mechanics of a game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They often serve as companions, quest-givers, merchants and much more.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Their realism has advanced significantly in the past few years, thanks to improvements in AI technologies.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs are essential in both narrative-driven as well as open-world games.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They help convey the lore and context of the game, making them pivotal to world-building and narrative progression.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, an NPC can provide critical information, offer quests, or simply populate the world to add a sense of realism to the game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, their role as quest-givers or merchants makes them integral to the gameplay loop, giving players access to resources, missions, or services that enable further progression.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, NPCs can be designed to serve functional roles in games, such as a merchant or to provide a service to the player.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These characters are central to facilitating game mechanics by acting as intermediaries between the player and in-game systems.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Academics say the interactions between players and NPCs are often designed to be straightforward but contextually relevant, ensuring that the player receives necessary feedback or resources for gameplay continuity.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in artificial intelligence have significantly enhanced the complexity and realism of NPCs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before these advancements, AI operated on pre-programmed behaviors, making them predictable and repeatable.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] With AI developing NPCs have become more adaptive and able to dynamically respond to players.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts think the integration of deep learning and reinforcement learning techniques has enabled NPCs to adjust their behavior in response to player actions, creating a more interactive and personalized gameplay experience.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] One such development is the use of adaptive behavior models.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These allow NPCs to analyze and learn from players decisions in real time.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This behavior allows for a much more engaging experience.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example as said by experts in the field, NPCs in modern video games can now react to player actions with increased sophistication, such as adjusting their tactics in combat or changing their dialogue based on past interactions.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] By using deep learning algorithms these systems emulate human-like decisions-making, thus making NPCs feel more like real people rather than static game elements.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another advancements in NPC AI is the use of natural language processing, which allows NPCs to engage in more realistic conversations with players.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Before this NPC dialogue was limited to a fixed set of responses.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It is said that NLP has improved the fluidity of NPC conversations, allowing them to respond more contextually to player inputs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This development has increased the depth and immersion of player-NPC interactions, as players can now engage in more complex dialogues that affect the storyline and gameplay outcomes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Additionally, deep learning models have allowed NPCs to become more capable of predicting players behaviors.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Deep learning allows NPCs to process large amounts of data and adapt to player strategies, making interactions with them less predictable and more varied.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This creates a more immersive experience, as NPCs are now able to "learn" from player behavior, which provides a greater sense of realism within the game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have led to more complex and adaptive behaviors in non-playable characters (NPCs).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For instance, AI systems now utilize sophisticated techniques such as decision trees and state machines to enhance NPC interactions and realism, as discussed in "Artificial Intelligence in Games".
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Recent advancements in AI for video games have also focused on improving dynamic and adaptive behaviors in NPCs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, recent research has explored the use of complex neural networks to enable NPCs to learn and adapt their behavior based on player actions, enhancing the overall gaming experience.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This approach is detailed in the IEEE paper on "AI Techniques for Interactive Game Systems".
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Despite all of these advancements in NPC AI, there are still significant challenges that developers face in designing NPCs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] They need to balance realism, functionally, and players expectations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The key challenge is to make sure that NPCs enhance the players experience, rather than disturb the gameplay.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Overly realistic NPCs that behave unpredictably can frustrate players by hindering progression or breaking immersion.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Conversely, NPCs that are too predictable or simplistic may fail to engage players, reducing the overall effectiveness of the game's narrative and mechanics.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Another factor that needs to be accounted for is the computation cost of implementing advanced AI for NPCs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of these Advanced AI techniques requires large amount of processing power, which can limit its usage.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Balancing the performance of AI-driven NPCs with the game's overall technical limitations is crucial for ensuring smooth gameplay.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Experts mentioned how developers must allocate resources efficiently to avoid overburdening the game's systems, particularly in large, open-world games where numerous NPCs must interact with the player simultaneously.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Finally, creating NPCs that can respond dynamically to a wide range of player behaviors remains a difficult task.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NPCs must be able to handle both scripted interactions and unscripted scenarios where players may behave in unexpected ways.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Designing NPCs capable of adapting to such variability requires complex AI models that can account for numerous possible interactions, which can be resource-intensive and time-consuming for developers.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the context of artificial intelligence in video games, cheating refers to the programmer giving agents actions and access to information that would be unavailable to the player in the same situation.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Believing that the Atari 8-bit could not compete against a human player, Chris Crawford did not fix a bug in *Eastern Front (1941)* that benefited the computer-controlled Russian side.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Computer Gaming World* in 1994 reported that "It is a well-known fact that many AIs 'cheat' (or, at least, 'fudge') in order to be able to keep up with human players".
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, if the agents want to know if the player is nearby they can either be given complex, human-like sensors (seeing, hearing, etc.), or they can cheat by simply asking the game engine for the player's position.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Common variations include giving AIs higher speeds in racing games to catch up to the player or spawning them in advantageous positions in first-person shooters.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The use of cheating in AI shows the limitations of the "intelligence" achievable artificially; generally speaking, in games where strategic creativity is important, humans could easily beat the AI after a minimum of trial and error if it were not for this advantage.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheating is often implemented for performance reasons where in many cases it may be considered acceptable as long as the effect is not obvious to the player.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While cheating refers only to privileges given specifically to the AI—it does not include the inhuman swiftness and precision natural to a computer—a player might call the computer's inherent advantages "cheating" if they result in the agent acting unlike a human player.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sid Meier stated that he omitted multiplayer alliances in *Civilization* because he found that the computer was almost as good as humans in using them, which caused players to think that the computer was cheating.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Developers say that most game AIs are honest but they dislike players erroneously complaining about "cheating" AI.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, humans use tactics against computers that they would not against other people.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In short, cheating AI is when the game seems to break its own rules, producing impossible outcomes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The opposite is dynamic difficulty, a structured adjustment of AI skill to maintain competition, respecting game mechanics.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Some games may have a blend of both of these systems at once.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 1996 game *Creatures*, the user "hatches" small furry animals and teaches them how to behave.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] These "Norns" can talk, feed themselves, and protect themselves against vicious creatures.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] It was the first popular application of machine learning in an interactive simulation.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Neural networks are used by the creatures to learn what to do.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The game is regarded as a breakthrough in artificial life research, which aims to model the behavior of creatures interacting with their environment.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In the 2001 first-person shooter *Halo: Combat Evolved* the player assumes the role of the Master Chief, battling various aliens on foot or in vehicles.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Enemies use cover very wisely, and employ suppressing fire and grenades.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The squad situation affects the individuals, so certain enemies flee when their leader dies.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Attention is paid to the little details, with enemies notably throwing back grenades or team-members responding to being bothered.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The underlying "behavior tree" technology has become very popular in the games industry since *Halo 2*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2005 psychological horror first-person shooter *F.E.A.R.* has player characters engage a battalion of cloned super-soldiers, robots and paranormal creatures.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI uses a planner to generate context-sensitive behaviors, the first time in a mainstream game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This technology is still used as a reference for many studios.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The Replicas are capable of utilizing the game environment to their advantage, such as overturning tables and shelves to create cover, opening doors, crashing through windows, or even noticing (and alerting the rest of their comrades to) the player's flashlight.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In addition, the AI is also capable of performing flanking maneuvers, using suppressing fire, throwing grenades to flush the player out of cover, and even playing dead.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Most of these actions, in particular the flanking, is the result of emergent behavior.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The survival horror series *S.T.A.L.K.E.R.* (2007–) confronts the player with man-made experiments, military soldiers, and mercenaries known as Stalkers.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The various encountered enemies (if the difficulty level is set to its highest) use combat tactics and behaviors such as healing wounded allies, giving orders, out-flanking the player and using weapons with pinpoint accuracy.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2010 real-time strategy game *StarCraft II: Wings of Liberty* gives the player control of one of three factions in a 1v1, 2v2, or 3v3 battle arena.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The player must defeat their opponents by destroying all their units and bases.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] This is accomplished by creating units that are effective at countering opponents' units.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Players can play against multiple different levels of AI difficulty ranging from very easy to Cheater 3 (insane).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The AI is able to cheat at the difficulty Cheater 1 (vision), where it can see units and bases when a player in the same situation could not.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Cheater 2 gives the AI extra resources, while Cheater 3 gives an extensive advantage over its opponent.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence, AI systems that can respond to prompts and produce text, images, and audio and video clips, arose in 2023 with systems like ChatGPT and Stable Diffusion.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In video games, these systems could create the potential for game assets to be created indefinitely, bypassing typical limitations on human creations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] For example, the 2024 browser-based sandbox game *Infinite Craft* uses generative AI software, including LLaMA.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] When two elements are being combined, a new element is generated by the AI.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2024 browser-based game *Oasis* uses generative AI to simulate the video game *Minecraft*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* is trained on millions of hours of footage from *Minecraft*, and predicts how the next frame of gameplay looks using this dataset.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] *Oasis* does not have object permanence because it does not store any data.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The 2025 video game *AI2U: With You 'Til The End*, developed by AlterStaff Inc., used ChatGPT for the non-playable characters dialogue in the game.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Generative artificial intelligence has been included to perform video upscaling of game images.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Both NVidia's Deep Learning Super Sampling (DLSS) and AMD's FidelityFX Super Resolution (FSR) have included AI as part of their engine.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] In March 2026, NVidia announced version 5.0 of DLSS to release later in 2026, which among other improvements, includes an AI engine that "infuses pixels with photoreal lighting and materials" as to make existing game graphics appear more realistic.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] NVidia's Jensen Huang said that developers will far more control over how DLSS 5.0 would interact with their games, allowing the developer to tweak lighting and texture adjustments, and that NVidia was continuing to improve the technology before its release.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] However, there are similar concerns in other fields particularly the potential for loss of jobs normally dedicated to the creation of these assets.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Voice actors were one of the first groups to express concern on generative AI use in video games.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The North American actor's union SAG-AFTRA had finished a strike in 2023 against television and film production companies, with the strike concluded on new contract terms that gave actors strong control over whether their voices could be used to train generative AI engines.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Shortly afterward, the union agreed to a contract with AI company Replica Studios to allow union voices to be used to train AI and used in games, with the contract assuring pay and rights protections.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] While the contract was agreed upon by a SAG-AFTRA committee, many members expressed criticism of the move, having not been told of it until it was completed and that the deal did not do enough to protect the actors.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] The strike concluded by July 2025 with the affected publishers agreeing to a contract that gave actors stronger control of whether their voices could be used for AI.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] To assure such content was disclosed by game publishers and avoid potential copyright issues, Valve implemented new requirements for games on Steam that the use of pre-generated AI assets or live generation via generative AI must be disclosed on the storefront page.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/artificial-intelligence-in-video-games] Sweeney criticized this move, as "it makes it much, much, much harder for a game developer to have a chance of success.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm finds the shortest path from a given source node to every other node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be used to find the shortest path to a specific destination node, by terminating the algorithm after determining the shortest path to that node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the nodes of the graph represent cities, and the costs of edges represent the distances between pairs of cities connected by a direct road, then Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to find the shortest route between one city and all other cities.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A common application of shortest path algorithms is network routing protocols, most notably IS-IS (Intermediate System to Intermediate System) and OSPF (Open Shortest Path First).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It is also employed as a subroutine in algorithms such as Johnson's algorithm.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm uses a min-priority queue data structure for selecting the shortest paths known so far.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Before more advanced priority queue structures were discovered, Dijkstra's original algorithm ran in $\Theta (|V|^{2})$ time, where $|V|$ is the number of nodes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Fredman & Tarjan 1984 proposed a Fibonacci heap priority queue to optimize the running time complexity to $\Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)$ , where $|E|$ is the number of edges.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is asymptotically the fastest known single-source shortest-path algorithm for arbitrary directed graphs with unbounded non-negative weights.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, specialized cases (such as bounded/integer weights, directed acyclic graphs etc.) can be improved further.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If preprocessing is allowed, algorithms such as contraction hierarchies can be up to seven orders of magnitude faster.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is commonly used on graphs where the edge weights are positive integers or real numbers.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] It can be generalized to any graph where the edge weights are partially ordered, provided the subsequent labels (a subsequent label is produced when traversing an edge) are monotonically non-decreasing.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In many fields, particularly artificial intelligence, Dijkstra's algorithm or a variant offers a uniform cost search and is formulated as an instance of the more general idea of best-first search.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] — Edsger Dijkstra, in an interview with Philip L.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra thought about the shortest path problem while working as a programmer at the Mathematical Center in Amsterdam in 1956.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He wanted to demonstrate the capabilities of the new ARMAC computer.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] His objective was to choose a problem and a computer solution that non-computing people could understand.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] He designed the shortest path algorithm and later implemented it for ARMAC for a slightly simplified transportation map of 64 cities in the Netherlands (he limited it to 64, so that 6 bits would be sufficient to encode the city number).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A year later, he came across another problem advanced by hardware engineers working on the institute's next computer: minimize the amount of wire needed to connect the pins on the machine's back panel.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As a solution, he re-discovered Prim's minimal spanning tree algorithm (known earlier to Jarník, and also rediscovered by Prim).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra published the algorithm in 1959, two years after Prim and 29 years after Jarník.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The algorithm requires a starting node, and computes the shortest distance from that starting node to each other node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assign to every node a distance from start value: for the starting node, it is zero, and for all other nodes, it is infinity, since initially no path is known to these nodes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] During execution, the distance of a node *N* is the length of the shortest path discovered so far between the starting node and *N*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the unvisited set, select the current node to be the one with the smallest (finite) distance; initially, this is the starting node (distance zero).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the unvisited set is empty, or contains only nodes with infinite distance (which are unreachable), then the algorithm terminates by skipping to step 6.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the only concern is the path to a target node, the algorithm terminates once the current node is the target node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the current node, consider all of its unvisited neighbors and update their distances through the current node; compare the newly calculated distance to the one currently assigned to the neighbor and assign the smaller one to it.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if the current node *A* is marked with a distance of 6, and the edge connecting it with its neighbor *B* has length 2, then the distance to *B* through *A* is 6 + 2 = 8.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If B was previously marked with a distance greater than 8, then update it to 8 (the path to B through A is shorter).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Otherwise, keep its current distance (the path to B through A is not the shortest).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After considering all of the current node's unvisited neighbors, the current node is removed from the unvisited set.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Thus a visited node is never rechecked, which is correct because the distance recorded on the current node is minimal (as ensured in step 3), and thus final.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once the loop exits (steps 3–5), every visited node contains its shortest distance from the starting node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The shortest path between two intersections on a city map can be found by this algorithm using pencil and paper.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every intersection is listed on a separate line: one is the starting point and is labeled (given a distance of) 0.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Every other intersection is initially labeled with a distance of infinity.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is done to note that no path to these intersections has yet been established.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At each iteration one intersection becomes the current intersection.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For the first iteration, this is the starting point.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From the current intersection, the distance to every neighbor (directly-connected) intersection is assessed by summing the label (value) of the current intersection and the distance to the neighbor and then relabeling the neighbor with the lesser of that sum and the neighbor's existing label.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] I.e., the neighbor is relabeled if the path to it through the current intersection is shorter than previously assessed paths.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If so, mark the road to the neighbor with an arrow pointing to it, and erase any other arrow that points to it.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After the distances to each of the current intersection's neighbors have been assessed, the current intersection is marked as visited.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The unvisited intersection with the smallest label becomes the current intersection and the process repeats until all nodes with labels less than the destination's label have been visited.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Once no unvisited nodes remain with a label smaller than the destination's label, the remaining arrows show the shortest path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following pseudocode, dist is an array that contains the current distances from the *source* to other vertices, i.e. dist[*u*] is the current distance from the source to the vertex *u*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The prev array contains pointers to previous-hop nodes on the shortest path from source to the given vertex (equivalently, it is the *next-hop* on the path *from* the given vertex *to* the source).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The code u ← vertex in *Q* with min dist[u], searches for the vertex *u* in the vertex set *Q* that has the least dist[*u*] value.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph.Distance(*u*,*v*) returns the length of the edge joining (i.e. the distance between) the two neighbor-nodes *u* and *v*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The variable *alt* on line 14 is the length of the path from the *source* node to the neighbor node *v* if it were to go through *u*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If this path is shorter than the current shortest path recorded for *v*, then the distance of *v* is updated to *alt*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To find the shortest path between vertices *source* and *target*, the search terminates after line 10 if *u* = *target*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Now sequence *S* is the list of vertices constituting one of the shortest paths from *source* to *target*, or the empty sequence if no path exists.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A more general problem is to find all the shortest paths between *source* and *target* (there might be several of the same length).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then instead of storing only a single node in each entry of prev[] all nodes satisfying the relaxation condition can be stored.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, if both *r* and *source* connect to *target* and they lie on different shortest paths through *target* (because the edge cost is the same in both cases), then both *r* and *source* are added to prev[*target*].
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When the algorithm completes, prev[] data structure describes a graph that is a subset of the original graph with some edges removed.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its key property is that if the algorithm was run with some starting node, then every path from that node to any other node in the new graph is the shortest path between those nodes graph, and all paths of that length from the original graph are present in the new graph.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Then to actually find all these shortest paths between two given nodes, a path finding algorithm on the new graph, such as depth-first search would work.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A min-priority queue is an abstract data type that provides 3 basic operations: add_with_priority(), decrease_priority() and extract_min().
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As mentioned earlier, using such a data structure can lead to faster computing times than using a basic queue.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Notably, Fibonacci heap or Brodal queue offer optimal implementations for those 3 operations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Instead of filling the priority queue with all nodes in the initialization phase, it is possible to initialize it to contain only *source*; then, inside the `**if** *alt* < dist[*v*]` block, the decrease_priority() becomes an add_with_priority() operation.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Yet another alternative is to add nodes unconditionally to the priority queue and to instead check after extraction (`*u* ← *Q*.extract_min()`) that it isn't revisiting, or that no shorter connection was found yet in the `if alt < dist[v]` block.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This can be done by additionally extracting the associated priority `*p*` from the queue and only processing further `**if** *p* == dist[*u*]` inside the `**while** *Q* is not empty` loop.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] These alternatives can use entirely array-based priority queues without decrease-key functionality, which have been found to achieve even faster computing times in practice.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] However, the difference in performance was found to be narrower for denser graphs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To prove the correctness of Dijkstra's algorithm, mathematical induction can be used on the number of visited nodes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The base case is when there is just one visited node, source.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Its distance is defined to be zero, which is the shortest distance, since negative weights are not allowed.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Assuming that the hypothesis holds for k visited nodes, to show it holds for $k+1$ nodes, let u be the next visited node, i.e. the node with minimum `dist[u]`.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The claim is that `dist[u]` is the shortest distance from source to u.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If a shorter path were available, then this shorter path either contains another unvisited node or not.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For all other visited nodes v, the `dist[v]` is already known to be the shortest distance from source, because of the inductive hypothesis, and these values are unchanged.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After processing u, it is still true that for each unvisited node w, `dist[w]` is the shortest distance from source to w using visited nodes only.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Any shorter path that did not use u, would already have been found, and if a shorter path used u it would have been updated when processing u.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] After all nodes are visited, the shortest path from source to any node v consists only of visited nodes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Therefore, `dist[v]` is the shortest distance.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Bounds of the running time of Dijkstra's algorithm on a graph with edges E and vertices V can be expressed as a function of the number of edges, denoted $|E|$ , and the number of vertices, denoted $|V|$ , using big-O notation.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The complexity bound depends mainly on the data structure used to represent the set Q.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In the following, upper bounds can be simplified because $|E|$ is $O(|V|^{2})$ for any simple graph, but that simplification disregards the fact that in some problems, other upper bounds on $|E|$ may hold.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] where $T_{\mathrm {dk} }$ and $T_{\mathrm {em} }$ are the complexities of the *decrease-key* and *extract-minimum* operations in Q, respectively.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The simplest version of Dijkstra's algorithm stores the vertex set Q as a linked list or array, and edges as an adjacency list or matrix.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In this case, extract-minimum is simply a linear search through all vertices in Q, so the running time is ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|^{2})=\Theta (|V|^{2})}$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To perform decrease-key steps in a binary heap efficiently, it is necessary to use an auxiliary data structure that maps each vertex to its position in the heap, and to update this structure as the priority queue Q changes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] With a self-balancing binary search tree or binary heap, the algorithm requires ${\textstyle \Theta ((|E|+|V|)\log |V|)}$ time in the worst case; for connected graphs this time bound can be simplified to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The Fibonacci heap improves this to ${\textstyle \Theta (|E|+|V|\log |V|)}$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In common presentations of Dijkstra's algorithm, initially all nodes are entered into the priority queue.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This is, however, not necessary: the algorithm can start with a priority queue that contains only one item, and insert new items as they are discovered (instead of doing a decrease-key, check whether the key is in the queue; if it is, decrease its key, otherwise insert it).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This variant has the same worst-case bounds as the common variant, but maintains a smaller priority queue in practice, speeding up queue operations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Moreover, not inserting all nodes in a graph makes it possible to extend the algorithm to find the shortest path from a single source to the closest of a set of target nodes on infinite graphs or those too large to represent in memory.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Combinations of such techniques may be needed for optimal practical performance on specific problems.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two distance arrays are maintained: *df*[*v*] (distance from s to v) and *db*[*v*] (distance from v to t), initialized to ∞ except *df*[*s*] = 0 and *db*[*t*] = 0.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Two priority queues *Qf* and *Qb* hold vertices not yet fully processed, and two sets *Sf* and *Sb* store vertices whose shortest-path distance is finalized in each direction.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A variable μ stores the length of the best full s–t path found so far, initially ∞.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] and symmetrically for the backward search.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A key feature is the stopping condition: once the sum of the current minimum priorities in both queues is at least μ, no yet-unsettled path can improve upon μ.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] At this point μ equals the true shortest-path distance δ(*s*,*t*), and the search terminates.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] This criterion avoids a common mistake of halting as soon as the two frontiers touch, which may overlook a shorter alternative crossing elsewhere.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because each search only needs to explore roughly half of the search space in typical graphs, the bidirectional method often visits far fewer vertices and relaxes far fewer edges than one-directional Dijkstra on single-pair queries.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In road-network–like graphs the savings can be dramatic, sometimes reducing the explored region from an exponential-size ball to two smaller half-balls.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The method is widely used in point-to-point routing for maps and navigation software and serves as a base for many speed-up techniques such as the ALT, contraction hierarchies, and reach-based routing.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] If the actual shortest path (not just its distance) is desired, predecessor pointers can be stored in both searches.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When μ is updated through some crossing vertex x, the algorithm records this meeting point and reconstructs the final route as the forward path from s to x concatenated with the backward path from x to t.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Theoretical research shows that an optimized bidirectional approach can be instance-optimal, meaning no correct algorithm can asymptotically relax fewer edges on the same graph instance.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Although Dijkstra's algorithm is optimal for graphs with non-negative edge weights, its practical runtime depends on both data structures and graph properties.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Using a binary heap results in a running time of O((V+E)logV).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Alternatives such as Fibonacci heaps provide better theoretical bounds but often perform worse in real applications because of large constant factors.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Graph structure also plays a major role.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Sparse networks, such as road maps, allow Dijkstra's algorithm to operate efficiently since most vertices have low degree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dense graphs increase relaxations and slow down the process.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of this, modern routing systems often use Dijkstra's algorithm together with preprocessing methods such as A* search, landmark heuristics, or contraction hierarchies, which significantly reduce the search space.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Memory locality is another important factor.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Cache-optimized priority queues and adjacency layouts can reduce latency for large graphs that exceed CPU cache limitations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Because of these considerations, most real-world systems use specialized Dijkstra variants tuned for specific graph families and hardware constraints.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] As well as simply computing distances and paths, Dijkstra's algorithm can be used to sort vertices by their distances from a given starting vertex.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To achieve this, they use a comparison-based heap whose cost of returning/removing the minimum element from the heap is logarithmic in the number of elements inserted after it rather than in the number of elements in the heap.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] When arc weights are small integers (bounded by a parameter C ), specialized queues can be used for increased speed.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The first algorithm of this type was Dial's algorithm for graphs with positive integer edge weights, which uses a bucket queue to obtain a running time $O(|E|+|V|C)$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The use of a Van Emde Boas tree as the priority queue brings the complexity to $O(|E|+|V|\log C/\log \log |V|C)$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Another interesting variant based on a combination of a new radix heap and the well-known Fibonacci heap runs in time $O(|E|+|V|{\sqrt {\log C}})$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's original algorithm can be extended with modifications.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] For example, sometimes it is desirable to present solutions which are less than mathematically optimal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] To obtain a ranked list of less-than-optimal solutions, the optimal solution is first calculated.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] A single edge appearing in the optimal solution is removed from the graph, and the optimum solution to this new graph is calculated.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Each edge of the original solution is suppressed in turn and a new shortest-path calculated.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The secondary solutions are then ranked and presented after the first optimal solution.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Dijkstra's algorithm is usually the working principle behind link-state routing protocols.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Unlike Dijkstra's algorithm, the Bellman–Ford algorithm can be used on graphs with negative edge weights, as long as the graph contains no negative cycle reachable from the source vertex *s*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The presence of such cycles means that no shortest path can be found, since the label becomes lower each time the cycle is traversed.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] (This statement assumes that a "path" is allowed to repeat vertices.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In graph theory that is normally not allowed.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] In theoretical computer science it often is allowed.) It is possible to adapt Dijkstra's algorithm to handle negative weights by combining it with the Bellman-Ford algorithm (to remove negative edges and detect negative cycles): Johnson's algorithm.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The A* algorithm is a generalization of Dijkstra's algorithm that reduces the size of the subgraph that must be explored, if additional information is available that provides a lower bound on the distance to the target.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The process that underlies Dijkstra's algorithm is similar to the greedy process used in Prim's algorithm.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's purpose is to find a minimum spanning tree that connects all nodes in the graph; Dijkstra is concerned with only two nodes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Prim's does not evaluate the total weight of the path from the starting node, only the individual edges.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] Breadth-first search can be viewed as a special-case of Dijkstra's algorithm on unweighted graphs, where the priority queue degenerates into a FIFO queue.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] The fast marching method can be viewed as a continuous version of Dijkstra's algorithm which computes the geodesic distance on a triangle mesh.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] From a dynamic programming point of view, Dijkstra's algorithm is a successive approximation scheme that solves the dynamic programming functional equation for the shortest path problem by the **Reaching** method.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/dijkstra-s-algorithm] is a paraphrasing of Bellman's principle of optimality in the context of the shortest path problem.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] For example, consider navigating a mobile robot inside a building to a distant waypoint.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] It should execute this task while avoiding walls and not falling down stairs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] A motion planning algorithm would take a description of these tasks as input, and produce the speed and turning commands sent to the robot's wheels.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Motion planning algorithms might address robots with a larger number of joints (e.g., industrial manipulators), more complex tasks (e.g. manipulation of objects), different constraints (e.g., a car that can only drive forward), and uncertainty (e.g. imperfect models of the environment or robot).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Motion planning has several robotics applications, such as autonomy, automation, and robot design in CAD software, as well as applications in other fields, such as animating digital characters, video game, architectural design, robotic surgery, and the study of biological molecules.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] A basic motion planning problem is to compute a continuous path that connects a start configuration S and a goal configuration G, while avoiding collision with known obstacles.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The robot and obstacle geometry is described in a 2D or 3D *workspace*, while the motion is represented as a path in (possibly higher-dimensional) configuration space.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] A configuration describes the pose of the robot, and the configuration space C is the set of all possible configurations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The set of configurations that avoids collision with obstacles is called the free space Cfree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The complement of Cfree in C is called the obstacle or forbidden region.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Often, it is prohibitively difficult to explicitly compute the shape of Cfree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] However, testing whether a given configuration is in Cfree is efficient.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] First, forward kinematics determine the position of the robot's geometry, and collision detection tests if the robot's geometry collides with the environment's geometry.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Target space is a subspace of free space which denotes where we want the robot to move to.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] In global motion planning, target space is observable by the robot's sensors.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] However, in local motion planning, the robot cannot observe the target space in some states.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] To solve this problem, the robot goes through several virtual target spaces, each of which is located within the observable area (around the robot).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] A virtual target space is called a sub-goal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Obstacle space is a space that the robot can not move to.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Obstacle space is not opposite of free space.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Low-dimensional problems can be solved with grid-based algorithms that overlay a grid on top of configuration space, or geometric algorithms that compute the shape and connectivity of Cfree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Exact motion planning for high-dimensional systems under complex constraints is computationally intractable.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Potential-field algorithms are efficient, but fall prey to local minima (an exception is the harmonic potential fields).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms avoid the problem of local minima, and solve many problems quite quickly.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] They are unable to determine that no path exists, but they have a probability of failure that decreases to zero as more time is spent.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms are currently considered state-of-the-art for motion planning in high-dimensional spaces, and have been applied to problems which have dozens or even hundreds of dimensions (robotic manipulators, biological molecules, animated digital characters, and legged robots).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches overlay a grid on configuration space and assume each configuration is identified with a grid point.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] At each grid point, the robot is allowed to move to adjacent grid points as long as the line between them is completely contained within Cfree (this is tested with collision detection).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] This discretizes the set of actions, and search algorithms (like A*) are used to find a path from the start to the goal.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] These approaches require setting a grid resolution.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Search is faster with coarser grids, but the algorithm will fail to find paths through narrow portions of Cfree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Furthermore, the number of points on the grid grows exponentially in the configuration space dimension, which make them inappropriate for high-dimensional problems.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Traditional grid-based approaches produce paths whose heading changes are constrained to multiples of a given base angle, often resulting in suboptimal paths.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Any-angle path planning approaches find shorter paths by propagating information along grid edges (to search fast) without constraining their paths to grid edges (to find short paths).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Grid-based approaches often need to search repeatedly, for example, when the knowledge of the robot about the configuration space changes or the configuration space itself changes during path following.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Incremental heuristic search algorithms replan fast by using experience with the previous similar path-planning problems to speed up their search for the current one.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] These approaches are similar to grid-based search approaches except that they generate a paving covering entirely the configuration space instead of a grid.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The paving is decomposed into two subpavings X−,X+ made with boxes such that X− ⊂ Cfree ⊂ X+.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Characterizing Cfree amounts to solve a set inversion problem.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Interval analysis could thus be used when Cfree cannot be described by linear inequalities in order to have a guaranteed enclosure.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The robot is thus allowed to move freely in X−, and cannot go outside X+.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] To both subpavings, a neighbor graph is built and paths can be found using algorithms such as Dijkstra or A*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] When a path is feasible in X−, it is also feasible in Cfree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] When no path exists in X+ from one initial configuration to the goal, we have the guarantee that no feasible path exists in Cfree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] As for the grid-based approach, the interval approach is inappropriate for high-dimensional problems, due to the fact that the number of boxes to be generated grows exponentially with respect to the dimension of configuration space.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] An illustration is provided by the three figures on the right where a hook with two degrees of freedom has to move from the left to the right, avoiding two horizontal small segments.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Nicolas Delanoue has shown that the decomposition with subpavings using interval analysis also makes it possible to characterize the topology of Cfree such as counting its number of connected components.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Given a bundle of rays around the current position attributed with their length hitting a wall, the robot moves into the direction of the longest ray unless a door is identified.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Such an algorithm was used for modeling emergency egress from buildings.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] One approach is to treat the robot's configuration as a point in a potential field that combines attraction to the goal, and repulsion from obstacles.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The resulting trajectory is output as the path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] This approach has advantages in that the trajectory is produced with little computation.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] However, they can become trapped in local minima of the potential field and fail to find a path, or can find a non-optimal path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The artificial potential fields can be treated as continuum equations similar to electrostatic potential fields (treating the robot like a point charge), or motion through the field can be discretized using a set of linguistic rules.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] A navigation function or a probabilistic navigation function are sorts of artificial potential functions which have the quality of not having minimum points except the target point.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Sampling-based algorithms represent the configuration space with a roadmap of sampled configurations.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] A basic algorithm samples N configurations in C, and retains those in Cfree to use as *milestones*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] A roadmap is then constructed that connects two milestones P and Q if the line segment PQ is completely in Cfree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Again, collision detection is used to test inclusion in Cfree.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] To find a path that connects S and G, they are added to the roadmap.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] If a path in the roadmap links S and G, the planner succeeds, and returns that path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] If not, the reason is not definitive: either there is no path in Cfree, or the planner did not sample enough milestones.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] These algorithms work well for high-dimensional configuration spaces, because unlike combinatorial algorithms, their running time is not (explicitly) exponentially dependent on the dimension of C.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] They are also (generally) substantially easier to implement.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] They are probabilistically complete, meaning the probability that they will produce a solution approaches 1 as more time is spent.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] However, they cannot determine if no solution exists.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Given basic *visibility* conditions on Cfree, it has been proven that as the number of configurations N grows higher, the probability that the above algorithm finds a solution approaches 1 exponentially.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Visibility is not explicitly dependent on the dimension of C; it is possible to have a high-dimensional space with "good" visibility or a low-dimensional space with "poor" visibility.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The experimental success of sample-based methods suggests that most commonly seen spaces have good visibility.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] A motion planner is said to be *complete* if the planner in finite time either produces a solution or correctly reports that there is none.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Most complete algorithms are geometry-based.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The performance of a complete planner is assessed by its computational complexity.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] When proving this property mathematically, one has to make sure, that it happens in finite time and not just in the asymptotic limit.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] This is especially problematic, if there occur infinite sequences (that converge only in the limiting case) during a specific proving technique, since then, theoretically, the algorithm will never stop.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Intuitive "tricks" (often based on induction) are typically mistakenly thought to converge, which they do only for the infinite limit.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] In other words, the solution exists, but the planner will never report it.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] This property therefore is related to Turing completeness and serves in most cases as a theoretical underpinning/guidance.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Planners based on a brute force approach are always complete, but are only realizable for finite and discrete setups.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] In practice, the termination of the algorithm can always be guaranteed by using a counter, that allows only for a maximum number of iterations and then always stops with or without solution.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] For realtime systems, this is typically achieved by using a watchdog timer, that will simply kill the process.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The watchdog has to be independent of all processes (typically realized by low level interrupt routines).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The asymptotic case described in the previous paragraph, however, will not be reached in this way.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] It will report the best one it has found so far (which is better than nothing) or none, but cannot correctly report that there is none.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] All realizations including a watchdog are always incomplete (except all cases can be evaluated in finite time).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Completeness can only be provided by a very rigorous mathematical correctness proof (often aided by tools and graph based methods) and should only be done by specialized experts if the application includes safety content.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] On the other hand, disproving completeness is easy, since one just needs to find one infinite loop or one wrong result returned.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Formal Verification/Correctness of algorithms is a research field on its own.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] The correct setup of these test cases is a highly sophisticated task.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Many algorithms have been developed to handle variants of this basic problem.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/motion-planning] Hybrid systems are those that mix discrete and continuous behavior.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] A **navigation mesh**, or **navmesh**, is an abstract data structure used in artificial intelligence applications to aid agents in pathfinding through complicated spaces.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] This approach has been known since at least the mid-1980s in robotics, where it has been called a **meadow map**, and was popularized in video game AI in 2000.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] A navigation mesh is a collection of two-dimensional convex polygons (a polygon mesh) that define which areas of an environment are traversable by agents.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] In other words, a character in a game could freely walk around within these areas unobstructed by trees, lava, or other barriers that are part of the environment.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] Adjacent polygons are connected to each other in a graph.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] Pathfinding within one of these polygons can be done trivially in a straight line because the polygon is convex and traversable.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] Pathfinding between polygons in the mesh can be done with one of the large number of graph search algorithms, such as A*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] Agents on a navmesh can thus avoid computationally expensive collision detection checks with obstacles that are part of the environment.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] Representing traversable areas in a 2D-like form simplifies calculations that would otherwise need to be done in the "true" 3D environment, yet unlike a 2D grid it allows traversable areas that overlap above and below at different heights.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] The polygons of various sizes and shapes in navigation meshes can represent arbitrary environments with greater accuracy than regular grids can.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] Navigation meshes can be created manually, automatically, or by some combination of the two.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] In video games, a level designer might manually define the polygons of the navmesh in a level editor.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] This approach can be quite labor intensive.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] Alternatively, an application could be created that takes the level geometry as input and automatically outputs a navmesh.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] It is commonly assumed that the environment represented by a navmesh is static – it does not change over time – and thus the navmesh can be created offline and be immutable.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] However, there has been some investigation of online updating of navmeshes for dynamic environments.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] In robotics, using linked convex polygons in this manner has been called "meadow mapping", coined in a 1986 technical report by Ronald C.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] Navigation meshes in video game artificial intelligence are usually credited to Greg Snook's 2000 article "Simplified 3D Movement and Pathfinding Using Navigation Meshes" in *Game Programming Gems*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/navigation-mesh] In 2001, J.M.P. van Waveren described a similar structure with convex and connected 3D polygons, dubbed the "Area Awareness System", used for bots in *Quake III Arena*.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Pathfinding is closely related to the shortest path problem, within graph theory, which examines how to identify the path that best meets some criteria (shortest, cheapest, fastest, etc) between two points in a large network.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] At its core, a pathfinding method searches a graph by starting at one vertex and exploring adjacent nodes until the destination node is reached, generally with the intent of finding the cheapest route.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Although graph searching methods such as a breadth-first search would find a route if given enough time, other methods, which "explore" the graph, would tend to reach the destination sooner.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] An analogy would be a person walking across a room; rather than examining every possible route in advance, the person would generally walk in the direction of the destination and only deviate from the path to avoid an obstruction, and make deviations as minor as possible.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Two primary problems of pathfinding are (1) to find a path between two nodes in a graph; and (2) the shortest path problem—to find the optimal shortest path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Basic algorithms such as breadth-first and depth-first search address the first problem by exhausting all possibilities; starting from the given node, they iterate over all potential paths until they reach the destination node.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] These algorithms run in $O(|V|+|E|)$ , or linear time, where V is the number of vertices, and E is the number of edges between vertices.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] The more complicated problem is finding the optimal path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] The exhaustive approach in this case is known as the Bellman–Ford algorithm, which yields a time complexity of $O(|V||E|)$ , or quadratic time.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] However, it is not necessary to examine all possible paths to find the optimal one.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Algorithms such as A* and Dijkstra's algorithm strategically eliminate paths, either through heuristics or through dynamic programming.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] By eliminating impossible paths, these algorithms can achieve time complexities as low as $O(|E|\log(|V|))$ .
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] The above algorithms are among the best general algorithms which operate on a graph without preprocessing.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] However, in practical travel-routing systems, even better time complexities can be attained by algorithms which can pre-process the graph to attain better performance.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] One such algorithm is contraction hierarchies.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A common example of a graph-based pathfinding algorithm is Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] This algorithm begins with a start node and an "open set" of candidate nodes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] At each step, the node in the open set with the lowest distance from the start is examined.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] The node is marked "closed", and all nodes adjacent to it are added to the open set if they have not already been examined.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] This process repeats until a path to the destination has been found.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Since the lowest distance nodes are examined first, the first time the destination is found, the path to it will be the shortest path.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Dijkstra's algorithm fails if there is a negative edge weight.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] In the hypothetical situation where Nodes A, B, and C form a connected undirected graph with edges AB = 3, AC = 4, and BC = −2, the optimal path from A to C costs 1, and the optimal path from A to B costs 2.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Dijkstra's Algorithm starting from A will first examine B, as that is the closest.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] It will assign a cost of 3 to it, and mark it closed, meaning that its cost will never be reevaluated.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Therefore, Dijkstra's cannot evaluate negative edge weights.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] However, since for many practical purposes there will never be a negative edgeweight, Dijkstra's algorithm is largely suitable for the purpose of pathfinding.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A* is a variant of Dijkstra's algorithm with a wide variety of use cases.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A* assigns a weight to each open node equal to the weight of the edge to that node plus the approximate distance between that node and the finish.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] This approximate distance is found by the heuristic, and represents a minimum possible distance between that node and the end.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] This allows it to eliminate longer paths once an initial path is found.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] If there is a path of length x between the start and finish, and the minimum distance between a node and the finish is greater than x, that node need not be examined.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A* uses this heuristic to improve on the behavior relative to Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] When the heuristic evaluates to zero, A* is equivalent to Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] As the heuristic estimate increases and gets closer to the true distance, A* continues to find optimal paths, but runs faster (by virtue of examining fewer nodes).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] When the value of the heuristic is exactly the true distance, A* examines the fewest nodes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] In many applications (such as video games) this is acceptable and even desirable, in order to keep the algorithm running quickly.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Pathfinding has a history of being included in video games with moving objects or NPCs.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Chris Crawford in 1982 described how he "expended a great deal of time" trying to solve a problem with pathfinding in *Tanktics*, in which computer tanks became trapped on land within U-shaped lakes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] "After much wasted effort I discovered a better solution: delete U-shaped lakes from the map", he said.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] The concept of hierarchical pathfinding predates its adoption by the video game industry and has its roots in classical artificial intelligence research.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] One of the earliest formal descriptions appears in Sacerdoti's work on ABSTRIPS (Abstraction-Based STRIPS) in 1974, which explored hierarchical search strategies in logic-based planning.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Later research, such as Hierarchical A* by Holte et al., further developed the theory of abstraction hierarchies in search problems.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] In the context of video games, the need for efficient planning on large maps with limited CPU time led to the practical implementation of hierarchical pathfinding algorithms.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A notable advancement was the introduction of Hierarchical Path-Finding A* (HPA*) by Botea et al. in 2004.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] HPA* partitions the map into clusters and precomputes optimal local paths between entrance points of adjacent clusters.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] At runtime, it plans an abstract path through the cluster graph, then refines that path within each cluster.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] This significantly reduces the search space and allows for near-optimal planning with much faster performance.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Partial-Refinement A* (PRA*), developed by Sturtevant and Buro, takes a similar approach but emphasizes interleaved planning and acting.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Instead of refining the entire path immediately, PRA* refines only the first few steps and continues refining the rest as needed during execution.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] This is especially useful in dynamic environments.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Similar techniques include navigation meshes (navmesh), used for geometric planning in games, and multimodal transportation planning, such as in variations of the travelling salesman problem that involve multiple transport types.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A hierarchical planner performs pathfinding in two phases: first, between clusters at a high level; then, within individual clusters at a low level.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] This structure enables guided local search with fewer nodes, resulting in high performance.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] The main drawback is the implementation complexity of maintaining abstraction layers and refinements.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A map with a size of 3000×2000 nodes contains 6 million tiles.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Planning a path directly on this scale, even with an optimized algorithm, is computationally intensive due to the vast number of graph nodes and possible paths.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A hierarchical approach divides the map into 300×200 node clusters, forming a 10×10 grid (100 clusters total).
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] The high-level abstract graph now contains only 100 nodes.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A path is planned between these clusters, which is computationally cheap.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Once the abstract path is found, each cluster on the path is processed using a regular A* planner to find the exact low-level route within.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] This two-stage process significantly improves efficiency while maintaining near-optimal path quality.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Multi-agent pathfinding is to find the paths for multiple agents from their current locations to their target locations without colliding with each other, while at the same time optimizing a cost function, such as the sum of the path lengths of all agents.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Many multi-agent pathfinding algorithms are generalized from A*, or based on reduction to other well studied problems such as integer linear programming.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] However, such algorithms are typically incomplete; in other words, not proven to produce a solution within polynomial time.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] Some parallel approaches, such as Collaborative Diffusion, are based on embarrassingly parallel algorithms spreading multi-agent pathfinding into computational grid structures, e.g., cells similar to cellular automata.
[src:pathfinding-navmesh/pathfinding] A different category of algorithms sacrifice optimality for performance by either making use of known navigation patterns (such as traffic flow) or the topology of the problem space.
